[9] Diarrhea - Cambodia (Prey Veng) cholera suspected
Date: Mon 26 Jul 2010
Source: The Phnom Penh Post [edited]
<http://www.phnompenhpost.com/index.php/2010072640760/National-news/prey-veng-prisoners-stricken-by-sickness.html>


An outbreak of acute watery diarrhea cases in Prey Veng provincial prison
has stricken 63 inmates, 5 of whom are in serious condition, the country's
top prison official said yesterday [25 Jul 2010].

One inmate died of the illness late last week [week of 19 Jul 2010] after
being taken to hospital, but Heng Hak, director of the Interior Ministry's
General Department of Prisons, said yesterday [25 Jul 2010] that many of
the sick prisoners were recovering.

"In Prey Veng prison, only one prisoner has died because of diarrhea, while
the number of inmates with diarrhea has increased to 63," Heng Hak said.
"Only 5 patients are in serious condition, while the others are only
slightly ill because they received medical treatment on time." He added
that he was concerned the inmates might be sick with cholera.

Nou Sophal, technical director of the Prey Veng Health Department, said
yesterday [25 Jul 2010] that he did not know whether tests were being run
for cholera.

A report released by the rights group Licadho last week [week of 19 Jul
2010] warned that Cambodia's prisons could be the most overcrowded in the
world in fewer than 10 years unless steps are taken to reduce inmate
totals. Overcrowding exacerbates poor hygiene and contributes to the spread
of illnesses such as diarrhea.

The outbreak in Prey Veng marks at least the 3rd time since May [2010] that
prison officials have sought intervention from health officials to address
a diarrhea outbreak.

In May [2010], Pursat provincial prison saw 54 inmates fall ill, Phun
Chhin, a prison researcher for Licadho, said yesterday [25 Jul 2010]. He
added, though, that the situation in the facility had since improved. "It
is better for the present time. Recently, the prisoners haven't encountered
[diarrhoea] again after they improved their sanitation and started drinking
boiled water," he said.

Earlier this month [July 2010], officials at Preah Sihanouk provincial
prison sent 5 inmates to hospital after 10 came down with severe vomiting
and diarrhea, an outbreak that was also attributed to poor sanitation.

[byline: Chrann Chamroeun]

